hook.real_world_problem:
Flipkart's search results page calls 8 microservices simultaneously: catalog, pricing, ratings, inventory, ads, recommendations, shipping, promotions.

**Blocking approach (Topic 11.4) — 8 threads all waiting:**
```java
// Sequential or using ExecutorService + Future.get():
for (String service : services) {
    HttpResponse<String> r = client.send(request, BodyHandlers.ofString());
    // Thread BLOCKED until each response arrives
    results.add(parse(r.body()));
}
// If each service takes 100ms: total = 800ms
```

**Async approach — 8 requests fire simultaneously, zero threads blocked:**
```java
List<CompletableFuture<ServiceResult>> futures = services.stream()
    .map(service -> client
        .sendAsync(buildRequest(service), BodyHandlers.ofString())
        .thenApply(response -> parse(response.body()))
        .exceptionally(ex -> defaultResult(service)))
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

CompletableFuture.allOf(futures.toArray(new CompletableFuture[0]))
    .thenRun(() -> {
        List<ServiceResult> results = futures.stream()
            .map(CompletableFuture::join)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
        assemblePage(results);
    })
    .join();
// 8 services in parallel → total = ~100ms (the slowest service)
```

This is the difference between `client.send()` (blocking, Topic 11.4) and `client.sendAsync()` (non-blocking, Topic 11.5). The only change is one method name — but the implications for throughput are enormous.

This topic combines everything: Module 10's CompletableFuture + Module 11's HttpClient. You've built to this point.

concept_explanation.send_async:
**`client.sendAsync()` — the non-blocking alternative to `send()`:**

```java
import java.net.http.*;
import java.util.concurrent.*;

HttpClient client = HttpClient.newHttpClient();
HttpRequest request = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.example.com/quotes/TCS"))
    .GET().build();

// BLOCKING (Topic 11.4):
HttpResponse<String> response = client.send(request,
    HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());  // thread BLOCKS here

// NON-BLOCKING (Topic 11.5):
CompletableFuture<HttpResponse<String>> future = client.sendAsync(request,
    HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());  // returns IMMEDIATELY — no blocking
// The thread is free to do other work
// future completes when the response arrives
```

**`sendAsync()` returns `CompletableFuture<HttpResponse<T>>`** — the same CF you learned in Topic 10.5, but produced by an HTTP operation.

From here, all CF operations apply: `thenApply()`, `thenCompose()`, `exceptionally()`, `allOf()`, `anyOf()`.

concept_explanation.chaining_parse:
**Chaining JSON parsing to the async response:**

```java
ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();

// Pattern: sendAsync → thenApply (check status) → thenApply (parse JSON):
CompletableFuture<StockQuote> quoteFuture = client
    .sendAsync(request, HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString())
    .thenApply(response -> {
        if (response.statusCode() != 200) {
            throw new RuntimeException("HTTP " + response.statusCode());
        }
        return response.body();
    })
    .thenApply(body -> {
        try {
            return mapper.readValue(body, StockQuote.class);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Parse error: " + e.getMessage(), e);
        }
    })
    .exceptionally(ex -> {
        System.err.println("Fetch failed: " + ex.getMessage());
        return StockQuote.empty();  // fallback
    });

// Don't block yet — the future is running in the background
// ... do other setup work ...

// Later, when you need the result:
StockQuote quote = quoteFuture.join();  // block here, result is likely already ready
```

concept_explanation.fan_out_collect:
**Fan-out pattern — multiple async requests simultaneously:**

```java
List<String> symbols = List.of("TCS", "RELIANCE", "INFY", "HDFC", "WIPRO");

// Fire ALL 5 requests simultaneously — none blocks:
List<CompletableFuture<StockQuote>> futures = symbols.stream()
    .map(symbol -> client
        .sendAsync(buildRequest(symbol), HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString())
        .thenApply(r -> r.statusCode() == 200 ? parseQuote(r.body()) : null)
        .exceptionally(ex -> null))
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

// Wait for ALL to complete:
CompletableFuture.allOf(futures.toArray(new CompletableFuture[0]))
    .thenRun(() -> {
        List<StockQuote> quotes = futures.stream()
            .map(CompletableFuture::join)  // join() is instant — already done
            .filter(Objects::nonNull)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());

        System.out.printf("Fetched %d quotes%n", quotes.size());
        quotes.forEach(q -> System.out.printf("%-12s ₹%,.0f  %+.1f%%%n",
            q.symbol(), q.price(), q.changePercent()));
    })
    .join();  // main thread blocks here until all done

// Total time: ~max(all response times), not ~sum
```

concept_explanation.error_handling_async:
**Error handling in async HTTP chains:**

```java
// Three layers of error: network, HTTP status, JSON parse
CompletableFuture<String> result = client
    .sendAsync(request, HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString())

    // Layer 1: check HTTP status
    .thenApply(response -> {
        int status = response.statusCode();
        if (status == 404) throw new RuntimeException("NOT_FOUND");
        if (status == 429) throw new RuntimeException("RATE_LIMITED");
        if (status >= 500) throw new RuntimeException("SERVER_ERROR:" + status);
        return response.body();
    })

    // Layer 2: parse JSON
    .thenApply(body -> {
        try { return mapper.readTree(body).path("result").asText(); }
        catch (Exception e) { throw new RuntimeException("PARSE_ERROR", e); }
    })

    // Layer 3: catch ANYTHING from above
    .exceptionally(ex -> {
        String cause = ex.getCause() != null ? ex.getCause().getMessage() : ex.getMessage();
        if (cause.startsWith("NOT_FOUND"))    return "[not found]"; 
        if (cause.startsWith("RATE_LIMITED")) return "[rate limited]";
        return "[error: " + cause + "]";
    });
```

concept_explanation.any_of_fastest:
**anyOf — first successful response wins:**

```java
// Redundant request to 3 CDN endpoints — use whichever responds first:
String[] cdnUrls = {
    "https://cdn1.example.com/data",
    "https://cdn2.example.com/data",
    "https://cdn3.example.com/data"
};

List<CompletableFuture<String>> futures = Arrays.stream(cdnUrls)
    .map(url -> client
        .sendAsync(
            HttpRequest.newBuilder().uri(URI.create(url)).GET().build(),
            HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString())
        .thenApply(HttpResponse::body)
        .exceptionally(ex -> null))
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

CompletableFuture.anyOf(futures.toArray(new CompletableFuture[0]))
    .thenAccept(fastest -> System.out.println("Fastest CDN: " + fastest))
    .join();
```

